		 	<span id="comment_score_65070689" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65070689); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Rinnon">Rinnon</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Rinnon">( 1474161 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65070689">		
		on Tuesday January 07, 2025 @02:36PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23571991&amp;cid=65070689">#65070689</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65070689"><p><div class="quote"><p>"My investors verbally promised they wouldn't enforce them, that they had never enforced them before -- and in '17 and '18 that was true -- no one was enforcing them,"</p></div><p>Honestly this is about as foolish as it gets. I'm not saying those clauses ought to be in there or not; I'm not saying the venture capitalists aren't lying scoundrels; but the contract is what you agreed to. If you didn't agree to it, change the contract before signing it, or don't sign it. I can't speak for the Chinese legal system specifically, but the reason we put things in writing, and then sign it, is so that we don't have to try to prove that the other party "promised" something.</p></div>
	</div>

